SLA100H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Basic features of the grammar. Acquisition of essential vocabulary for practical conversation and for comprehension. Development of reading and writing skills. (May not be taken by students who, in the judgment of the Department, qualify for entry into SLA210H1 or SLA220Y1).
SLA100H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions:
This course will combine online asynchronous and online synchronous meetings. Pre-recorded material (1 hour per week) will be made available for learning that is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. There will be four hours of online synchronous delivery as per the meeting schedule. 

LEC0101: 1 hour asynchronous; Mon: online synchronous 10-12; Wed: online synchronous, 11-12, Thurs: online synchronous, 10-11.

LEC0102: 1 hour asynchronous; Mon: online synchronous 10-12; Wed: online synchronous, 11-12, Thurs: online synchronous, 10-11.

LEC5101: 1 hour asynchronous; Mon: online synchronous 5-6pm; Wed: online synchronous 5-6pm; Thurs: online synchronous 5-7pm.

SLA101H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Basic features of the grammar. Acquisition of essential vocabulary for practical conversation and for comprehension. Development of reading and writing skills. (May not be taken by students who, in the judgment of the Department, qualify for entry into SLA210H1 or SLA220Y1).
SLA101H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions:
This class is delivered per the meeting schedule online. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

Pre-recorded material (1 hour per week) will be made available for learning that is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. There will be four hours of online synchronous delivery as per the meeting schedule. 

LEC0101: 1 hour asynchronous; Mon: online synchronous 10-12; Wed: online synchronous, 11-12, Thurs: online synchronous, 10-11. 

LEC5101: 1 hour asynchronous; Mon: online synchronous 5-6pm; Wed: online synchronous 5-6pm; Thurs: online synchronous 5-7pm.

SLA105Y1-Y-20209.courseDescription: Grammar, composition, and conversation. Readings from Czech literature. Open only to students with little or no knowledge of the language.
SLA105Y1-Y-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule online using BB Collaborate. Students will need a webcam and microphone. All study materials will be provided on Quercus

SLA106H1-F-20209.courseDescription: The course is aimed at a wide range of students with a general interest in Polish but no prior knowledge. A communicative based approach will be used throughout the course, where all four skills (speaking, reading, listening, and writing) will be practised, with the main emphasis on speaking. Students will engage in interactive language activities, participating in group and pair work according to a syllabus based on systematic grammatical progression.
SLA106H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule in-person. The class is also live-streamed (permitting synchronous delivery). Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA107Y1-Y-20209.courseDescription: Basic phonology, orthography, morphology and syntax of Bosnian, Croatian and Serbian. Development of the four basic language skills: reading, writing, listening, and speaking. Acquisition of essential vocabulary for practical conversation and for comprehension.
SLA107Y1-Y-20209.exclusion: native speakers of BCS, SLA257Y1, SLA237Y1
SLA107Y1-Y-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule online using BB Collaborate. Students will need a webcam and microphone. All study materials will be provided on Quercus.

SLA108Y1-Y-20209.courseDescription: Basic vocabulary, simple sentence patterns, essential morphology. Internet language laboratory drills. Intended for students with little or no knowledge of the language.
SLA108Y1-Y-20209.deliveryInstructions: Two hours of material will be pre-recorded, and delivered online asynchronously, learning is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. The online synchronous class will be on Thurs, 5 to 7pm. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA116H1-S-20209.courseDescription: The course is aimed at a wide range of students with a general interest in Polish who have already completed SLA106H or who have comparable basic knowledge of Pol. A communicative based approach will be used throughout the course, where all four skills (speaking, reading, listening, and writing) will be practised, with the main emphasis on speaking. Students will engage in interactive language activities, participating in group and pair work according to a syllabus based on systematic grammatical progression.
SLA116H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online only. There will be 4 hours of synchronous delivery. Students will need a webcam and microphone

SLA196H1-F-20209.courseDescription: In its long history Russia has fought numerous wars, both defensive and offensive, and these wars have inspired a rich, complex, contradictory poetic response. We examine Russian war narratives starting with the medieval period and ending with the Second World War and including epic poetry, songs, stories, novels, paintings, and films. We will study the depiction of war and the image of the soldier (or warrior) in different genres and time periods, as well as the historical circumstances in which the different works were produced and the respective audiences for which they were intended. All texts will be in English. Restricted to first-year students. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
SLA196H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule in-person. The class is also live-streamed (permitting synchronous delivery). Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA199H1-F-20209.courseDescription: The Central European Region of Galicia gave rise to a remarkable array of literary representations -- Austrian, Jewish, Polish, and Ukrainian -- animating fantastic creatures, powerful myths, deviant pleasures, and sublime stories. Bruno Schulz created shimmering peacocks, Leopold von Sacher-Masoch seized ecstasy through pain, and Ivan Franko investigated the effects of avarice and social decay.
SLA199H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA206H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Students who completed SLA106H and SLA116H or who have comparable basic knowledge of Polish further develop their speaking, listening, reading and writing skills by revising, consolidating and building on their knowledge. Upon completion, they will be able to communicate in more advanced everyday situations and have substantial familiarity with Polish grammar.
SLA206H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule in-person. The class is also live-streamed (permitting synchronous delivery). Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA207H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Students with a general interest in Polish who have completed SLA206H1 or who have a comparable level of Polish further develop their speaking, listening, writing, and reading skills by revising, consolidating, and building on their knowledge. Upon completion, they will be able to communicate in more advanced everyday situations and have substantial familiarity with Polish grammar.
SLA207H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule online. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA208Y1-Y-20209.courseDescription: Study of morphology through grammar drills; oral practice; reading of texts from Ukrainian literature.
SLA208Y1-Y-20209.deliveryInstructions: Two hours of material will be pre-recorded, and delivered online asynchronously, learning is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. The online synchronous class will be on Wed, 5 to 7pm. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA210H1-F-20209.courseDescription: This course is designed for students with Russian background, students raised in homes where Russian is/was spoken, who speak or merely understand basic Russian but are otherwise illiterate in Russian (cannot/have difficulty reading or writing). This course helps heritage learners of Russian develop/maintain writing and reading skills as well as develop cultural literacy. (Online course in 2011-2012).
SLA210H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This is an online course that combines synchronous and asynchronous delivery. Pre-recorded material (2 hours per week) will be made available for learning that is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. There will be a 2-hour online synchronous class (Tue, 12-2).

SLA214H1-S-20209.courseDescription: A course for students of Czech and Slovak, BCS and Russian. Improve your writing skills in a group of different Slavic language learners. Learn simple creative writing in different genres. This course presents a catalogue of different methods and strategies for individual learners at various stages of writing in a foreign language. Complements rather than substitutes for intermediate and advanced levels of the languages taught.
SLA214H1-S-20209.prerequisite: SLA105Y1 or SLA107Y1 or (SLA100H1 and SLA101H1)
SLA214H1-S-20209.corequisite: SLA204Y1 or (SLA257H1 and SLA277H1) or SLA220Y1 or SLA320Y1
SLA214H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online only, using Zoom meetings. There will be 2 hours online synchronous delivery each week by the schedule.

SLA215H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Some of the most important features of Czech and Slovak cultural history are introduced in a survey of the national myths, traditions and cultural trends. (Offered every three years)
SLA215H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule in-person. The class is also live-streamed (permitting synchronous delivery) using BB Collaborate. Students will need a webcam and microphone. All study materials will be provided on Quercus

SLA220Y1-Y-20209.courseDescription: Continuation of development of proficiency in speaking, reading, listening and writing. Review the basic and learning of new grammatical and syntactical structures, study of word formation and acquisition of active vocabulary. Reading of classical, contemporary, adapted, and non-adapted literary and mass-media texts. Culture and listening through animation.
SLA220Y1-Y-20209.exclusion: native speakers of Russian, including SLA210H1
SLA220Y1-Y-20209.deliveryInstructions:
LEC0101: 1 hour asynchronous; Mon: online synchronous, 11-12; Wed: online synchronous 10-12; Fri: online synchronous 10-11.  

 

LEC5101: 1 hour asynchronous; Mon: online synchronous, 5-7; Wed: online synchronous 5-6; Thu: online synchronous 5-6pm.

SLA226H1-F-20209.courseDescription: The Polish School in cinema, its predecessors and successors, their artistic accomplishments, major theoretical and thematic concerns, and their place on the map of European cinema. Films of Ford, Wajda, Polanski, Konwicki, Borowczyk, Has, Kawalerowicz, Zanussi, Kieslowski, and of the new generation of Polish film makers. Films and discussions in English. (Offered every three years)
SLA226H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will offer online, asynchronous delivery and in-person meetings. 1 hour of lecture material will be pre-recorded, and delivered for which learning is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. Tutorials are delivered in person (Wed, 1-2pm), which will also be live-streamed. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA227H1-F-20209.courseDescription: A survey of the most significant twentieth-century novels from Croatia, Serbia and Bosnia through a chronological selection of literary texts (poems, plays, novels) from the eighteenth to the twentieth century. The course places South Slavic literary developments within the broader context of European intellectual history as well as Balkan cultural and political life. Taught in English, all readings in English.
SLA227H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be pre-recorded, and delivered online asynchronously, learning is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. Online synchronous tutorials are delivered per the meeting schedule (12-1pm). Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA228H1-S-20209.courseDescription: A selection of twentieth century Ukrainian novels and short prose in English translation. From the avant-garde intellectual novel of the 1920s, through socialist realism, to the post-modernist prose of the 1990s. Authors include Pidmohylny, Antonenko-Davydovych, Honchar, Shevchuk, Andrukhovych and Zabuzhko.
SLA228H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online only, using BB Collaborate. There will be 2 hours online synchronous delivery each week as scheduled.

SLA229H1-S-20209.courseTitle: Writing with Images: Eastern and Central European History Through the Graphic Novel
SLA229H1-S-20209.courseDescription: This course examines how East and Central European graphic novelists retell the history of the 20th century in images and words. Our focus is the medium. How do comics effect the relationship between the personal and national? Can graphic novels substitute history textbooks?
SLA229H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule online (Zoom).  We will have an hour of asynchronous pre-recorded lectures plus online assignments, and an hour synchronous of discussion/group work. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA234H1-F-20209.courseDescription: A survey of the Russian cinematic tradition from its beginnings through the first decade following the disintegration of the USSR. The course examines the avant-garde cinema and film theory of the 1920s; the totalitarian esthetics of the 1920s-1940s and the ideological uses of film art; the revolution in film theory and practice in the 1950s-1960s; cinema as medium of cultural dissent and as witness to social change. Students also acquire basic skills of film analysis. Taught in English, all films subtitled in English.
SLA234H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will combine online asynchronous and synchronous delivery. 45 minutes will be delivered through non-synchronous, recorded lectures. Students will be asked to watch films non-synchronously on a weekly basis, on average about 90 minutes in length. There will be 1 in-person tutorial (50min) that will take place online on Tuesdays, from 3 to 4pm. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA235H1-S-20209.courseTitle: After Communism: Literature and Art Post-1989
SLA235H1-S-20209.courseDescription: This course examines the era inaugurated by the collapse of the state-socialist regimes in the former Eastern Bloc, marked by political turmoil, major economic restructuring, and social ambivalences. The course investigates topics such as: socialist legacy and nostalgia, mass emigrations and refugee crises, conflicts over national identity and borders, sociocultural anxieties about inclusion in the EU, perspectives on the future of socialist thought and practice in Eastern Europe.
SLA235H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online only, using Zoom. There will be 2 hours of synchronous delivery. Students will need a webcam and microphone. In addition to assigned texts and films, students will occasionally be required to watch short recorded lectures.

SLA238H1-F-20209.courseDescription: A selection of literary texts depicting the experience and perceptions of Ukrainians in Canada from the first immigrants to the present. Texts include works originally written in English, French and Ukrainian, but all readings are in English. Authors include: Kiriak, Kostash, Ryga, Galay, Suknaski, Kulyk Keefer.
SLA238H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule online. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA245H1-S-20209.courseTitle: The Golden Age of Russian Literature
SLA245H1-S-20209.courseDescription: A survey of Russian literature from1820-1900. Topics include: Romanticism and Realism; the myth of St. Petersburg; the Russian Empire and its borders; the individual and society; man and nature; the “woman question”; freedom and rationality. Readings may include: Pushkin, Lermontov, Gogol, Goncharov, Tolstoi, Turgenev, Dostoevskii, Saltykov-Shchedrin, Chekhov. Taught and read in English.
SLA245H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule online. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA247H1-S-20209.courseDescription: An overview of the Yugoslav and post-Yugoslav cinematic tradition from the 1960s to the present. Topics include revolution and socialism; cinema as activism; ideology and politics; sex and gender; war and trauma. Taught in English. All films with subtitles.
SLA247H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will combine online asynchronous and synchronous delivery. Lectures will be delivered through asynchronous recordings every two weeks. Students will be asked to watch films in their own time on a weekly basis. There will be a two-hour synchronous seminar that will take place online on Wed, from to 4pm. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA248H1-S-20209.courseTitle: Women and Women's Themes in Ukrainian Literature
SLA248H1-S-20209.courseDescription: This course examines the presentation of women and women's themes in works of Ukrainian literature. The subjects covered include: role models, freedom, socialism, nationalism, feminism, and sexuality.
SLA248H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online only, using BB Collaborate. There will be 2 hours online synchronous delivery each week as scheduled.

SLA252H1-S-20209.courseDescription: An exploration of the elements of the short story through close readings of works by 19th and 20th century writers. Stories in translation by Pushkin, Gogol, Turgenev, Dostoevsky, Chekhov, Olesha, Babel, and others. All readings in English.
SLA252H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule online. Tutorials are online only per meeting schedule. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA256H1-S-20209.courseTitle: Firebirds and Other Wonders: The World of Slavic Folklore
SLA256H1-S-20209.courseDescription: An introduction to the comparative study of folk narratives – fairy-tales, legends, epics, from Russia, Central and Eastern Europe, and the Balkans. Topics include the structural and psychological analysis and interpretation of oral folk traditions; the cultural specificity of Slavic folklore; its adaptation and treatment in literature, music, and visual arts. Taught in English, all readings in English.
SLA256H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule online. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA266H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Poland and Europe 1914-1945. As we commemorate the centenary of the outbrake of WWI, this cataclysmic event that launched the 20th century and was followed by another total war soon after still defines our view of the world and understanding of it. It may be time now to look anew at how various forms of expression, including literature, film, theatre, painting and sculpture produced during the two wars, between them or many decades later deal with the extreme and everyday experiences, with shattered worlds of individuals, ethnicities, and nations.
SLA266H1-F-20209.prerequisite: SLA216H1 or permission of the instructor
SLA266H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will offer online, asynchronous delivery and with an online synchronous meeting. 1 hour of lecture material will be pre-recorded, and delivered for which learning is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. Tutorials are delivered online (Tue, 1-2). Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA268H1-F-20209.courseDescription: How are Cossacks depicted in literary and visual works? Were they the agents of a repressive Russian government, the hirelings of Polish kings, the tormentors of Eastern European Jews, the protectors of Europe from the Ottomans, or the liberators of the Ukrainian nation? We read works from the Jewish, Polish, Russian and Ukrainian cultural traditions.
SLA268H1-F-20209.exclusion: CCR199H1 (First-Year Seminar: The Cossacks), offered in Winter 2012, Winter 2013, Fall 2013, Fall 2015, Fall 2016, and Fall 2017
SLA268H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule online. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA306H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Through a series of thematic modules based on everyday communicative situations in contemporary Poland students develop Polish language skills in the four linguistic competencies: listening, reading, writing, and speaking. The course is based on a communicative-functional approach to language. It means that even though students are regularly exposed to new grammatical structures, their work focuses primarily on practical, diverse uses of language in real-life situations.
SLA306H1-F-20209.prerequisite: SLA206Y1 or SLA207H1 or permission of instructor
SLA306H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will offer online asynchronous delivery and online, synchronous meetings. 2 hours of material will be pre-recorded, and delivered for which learning is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. Tutorials are delivered online (Tue, 3-5). Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA308Y1-Y-20209.courseDescription: Development of advanced speaking, reading, listening and writing skills on a wide variety of topics. Work on grammar and vocabulary building. Review of morphology and study of syntax. Short compositions. Expressing a written formal argument or opinion.
SLA308Y1-Y-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule online. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA311H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Fantastic and grotesque works by the most hilarious, obsessive, and delusional character in Russian literature, who teased, fascinated, and polarized readers. Gogol’s writings are examined through various theoretical approaches. Includes cinematic (Taras Bulba, Viy, Overcoat) and musical (Shostakovich’s “Nose”) re-creations of Gogol’s works. Taught in English, all readings in English.
SLA311H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule in-person. The class is also live-streamed (permitting synchronous delivery) and sessions will be recorded. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA312H1-S-20209.courseDescription: A study of Vladimir Nabokov's novels written in Europe and the United States. Special attention is paid to the nature and evolution of Nabokov's aesthetics; the place of his novels in European and American literary traditions; Nabokov's creative uses of exile to artistic, philosophical and ideological ends; the aesthetic and cultural implications of the writers' switch from Russian to English. Novels studied: Defense, Despair, The Gift, The Real Life of Sebastian Knight, Lolita, Pnin, Pale Fire. Taught in English, all readings in English.
SLA312H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online only, using Zoom meetings. There will be 2 hours online synchronous delivery each week by the schedule.

SLA320Y1-Y-20209.courseDescription: A survey of Russian culture and history of the 20th century through non-adapted readings and film. Development of advanced speaking, reading, listening and writing skills on a wide variety of topics. Work on grammar and vocabulary building. Subordinate and relative clauses, aspect, verbs of motion, participles and gerunds. Class is conducted primarily in Russian.
SLA320Y1-Y-20209.exclusion: native speakers of Russian, including SLA210H1
SLA320Y1-Y-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will combine online asynchronous and online synchronous meetings. Pre-recorded material (1 hour per week) will be made available for learning that is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. The rest of the schedule will be through online synchronous delivery (Tu, 10-12, R, 10-11, Fri, 10-11).

SLA322H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Language, life and the media in contemporary Russia. The course will be based on reading Russian newspapers, listening to Russian media, and discussing contemporary events in Russia.
SLA322H1-S-20209.exclusion: Heritage and native speakers of Russian
SLA322H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online only. There will be 2 hours online synchronous delivery each week by the schedule.

SLA323H1-S-20209.courseDescription: This course introduces Russian's sounds, structures, and alternations. Russian’s tricky morphologic alternations and their historical causes are explored while students master the hidden encoding of forms through study of the writing system, root structures, and variation.
SLA323H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: At this time, the University has not made a final decision about course delivery for the Winter 2021 term. The Faculty of Arts & Science will be updating Winter term course delivery information based on public health guidelines.

SLA330H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Structure and history of the first Slavic literary language. Reading and linguistic study of Old Slavonic texts.
SLA330H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule online. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA336H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Students expand their practical knowledge of Polish by engaging with online media and current issues in culture and society. They enrich their vocabulary, grammatical structures, and use of diverse stylistic registers while fine-tuning reading, writing, listening, and speaking skills.
SLA336H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule online. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA337H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Morphology, syntax, composition and translation, oral practice. Extensive reading, translation and analysis of contemporary Bosnian, Croatian and Serbian texts representing diverse styles.
SLA337H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online only, using Zoom. There will be 4 hours of synchronous delivery. Students will need a webcam and microphone

SLA343H1-S-20209.courseDescription: A survey of artistic and intellectual life in the USSR from the post-Stalinist “Thaw” period to the collapse of the Soviet empire and its cultural aftermath in the 1990s. Topics include: the recovery of suppressed cultural memory; the fluid boundaries between official and unofficial cultures; internal and external exile; Aesopian language; alternative modes of creation and dissemination (samizdat, tamizdat, unauthorized exhibitions and concerts, etc.); Russian conceptualism and post-modernism. Taught in English, readings in English.
SLA343H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will combine online asynchronous components and online synchronous meetings. Lectures delivered in class will be recorded and participation will include regular asynchronous online discussion.

SLA346H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Probes the paradoxes of politics, culture and everyday life by analyzing the complex coexistence of art and literature with changing cultural politics in a totalitarian and post-totalitarian system, with simplistic ideology and political dissent, and with prevailing myths about the West and the East. Readings in English (Polish for majors).
SLA346H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online (Zoom). There will be 2 hours synchronous delivery online: lecture plus discussion.

SLA357H1-S-20209.courseDescription: This course examines novels and short stories by writers from the former Yugoslavia (including Dubravka Ugrešić, Aleksandar Hemon) that thematize exile, migration, and displacement. Alongside literary works, we will read theoretical essays that speak to concepts of home, nation, and language. Taught in English. Readings in English.
SLA357H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be offered online with 2 hours of synchronous delivery every Thu. 12-14.00. There will be occasional asynchronous pre-recorded lectures.

SLA358H1-S-20209.courseTitle: Breaking Away from Empire: Ukrainian Fiction Since Independence
SLA358H1-S-20209.courseDescription: This course traces the extraordianry development of Ukrainian prose since the collapse of the Soviet Union. We will explore post-modernist _uphoria, colonial angst, cultural entropy, hooliganism, national identity, gender issues, and other aspects of modern Ukraine. All readings in English.
SLA358H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online only, using BB Collaborate. There will be 2 hours online synchronous delivery each week as scheduled.

SLA367H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Selected stories, plays; stylistic, structural, and thematic analysis, literary and historical context, influence in Russia and the West. Taught in English, all readings in English.
SLA367H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online only. There will be 2 hours online synchronous delivery each week as per the schedule. Students will need a mike and a webcam.

SLA410H1-S-20209.courseDescription: The course helps advanced heritage learners further to develop their active command of Russian. Special focus on speaking and writing skills, as well as cultural competence. Taught in Russian, all materials in Russian.
SLA410H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule online. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

LEC-0101.meetingStatusNotes: Oct 30, 2020: Delivery method and day/time changed.

SLA420Y1-Y-20209.courseTitle: Studies in Russian Syntax and Stylistics
SLA420Y1-Y-20209.courseDescription: Syntactic structures and their relation to meaning and style, word order, intonation. Consolidation of morphology, vocabulary building through extensive reading. Translation, composition, and oral practice.
SLA420Y1-Y-20209.exclusion: native speakers of Russian, including SLA210H1
SLA420Y1-Y-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered online per the meeting schedule. Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA421H1-F-20209.courseTitle: Introduction to Russian Poetry and Poetics
SLA421H1-F-20209.courseDescription: A study of the main principles of Russian prosody (meter, rhythm, rhyme, phonetic instrumentation, verse, stanza, genre) in relation to the creation of meaning of a poetic text. The formal aspects of Russian versification are examined in their historical evolution from the 18th century to the present, in both "classical" and "experimental" poetic modes. Taught in Russian, readings in Russian and English.
SLA421H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule in-person. The class is also live-streamed (permitting synchronous delivery). Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA422H1-S-20209.courseDescription: A survey of the golden age of Russian poetry with special attention to the evolution of verse forms and poetic genres. In this course students acquire advanced skills in the close reading of poetic forms and in their contextual historical analysis and interpretation. Taught in Russian, readings in Russian and English.
SLA422H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This class is delivered per the meeting schedule in-person. The class is also live-streamed (permitting synchronous delivery). Students will need a webcam and microphone.

SLA498Y1-Y-20209.courseDescription: A year-long research project (primarily for majors in Slavic POSts) on an approved major topic in a Slavic literature or culture, or Slavic linguistics, supervised by one of the Department’s instructors. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
SLA498Y1-Y-20209.webTimetableInstructions: For 'E' indicator courses: contact the department for further information at slavic@chass.utoronto.ca or 416-926-2075.

SLA499H1-F-20209.courseDescription: A semester-long research project (primarily for majors in Slavic POSts) on an approved major topic in a Slavic literature or culture, or Slavic linguistics, supervised by one of the Department’s instructors. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
SLA499H1-F-20209.webTimetableInstructions: For 'E' indicator courses: contact the department for further information at slavic@chass.utoronto.ca or 416-926-2075.

SLA499H1-S-20209.courseDescription: A semester-long research project (primarily for majors in Slavic POSts) on an approved major topic in a Slavic literature or culture, or Slavic linguistics, supervised by one of the Department’s instructors. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
SLA499H1-S-20209.webTimetableInstructions: For 'E' indicator courses: contact the department for further information at slavic@chass.utoronto.ca or 416-926-2075.
SLA499H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: At this time, the University has not made a final decision about course delivery for the Winter 2021 term. The Faculty of Arts & Science will be updating Winter term course delivery information based on public health guidelines.
